On Monday, October 27, 2003, at 09:12 AM, tengfei_liu1979 wrote:

&gt; Hi Dave,
&gt;
&gt; I am a new cantera user and my major is chemical engineering. We are
&gt; trying to develp a plug flow reactor model for catalytic (on Pt
&gt; surface) partial methane oxidation, which can be expressed by :
&gt; CH4+0.5O2=CO+2H2. I noticed that someone has already posted a
&gt; message about PFR model and you mentioned that we can use dz=V(gas)
&gt; *dt to convert the zero-dimentional model to a plug flow reactor.
&gt; Here, I have several questions about the zero dimentional model
&gt; surfreactor.m:
&gt;
&gt; 1) Is the kinetics also valid for the Partial Oxidation of Methane
&gt; on Pt surface, or, where did u get the original kinetics of the Pt
&gt; combustion?
&gt;
The mechanism for catalytic combustion on Pt is published in

     O. Deutschmann, R. Schmidt, F. Behrendt, J. Warnatz. Numerical  
Modeling of Catalytic Ignition. Proc. Combust. Inst. 26 (1996)  
1747-1754.

Please consult this paper for more information about the mechanism.


&gt; 2) In surfreactor.m, you wrote:
&gt;
&gt; t = 870.0;
&gt; gas = importPhase(&#39;ptcombust.cti&#39;,&#39;gas&#39;);
&gt;
&gt; % set the initial conditions
&gt; set(gas,&#39;T&#39;,t,&#39;P&#39;,oneatm,&#39;X&#39;,&#39;CH4:0.02, O2:0.21, N2:0.784&#39;);
&gt;
&gt; surf = importInterface(&#39;ptcombust.cti&#39;,&#39;Pt_surf&#39;, gas);
&gt; setTemperature(surf, t);
&gt;
&gt; Does this mean you set both the Pt wall surface and the inlet gas as
&gt; the same temperature? If the answer is yes, why should we do like
&gt; that, cause, I think the inlet gas might enter the reactor in a much
&gt; lower temperature and be heated by the hotter wall until it reaches
&gt; a considerable high temperature to ignite the reaction.
&gt;
The state of the gas object is used to represent the initial conditions  
when the Reactor object is created. Since this calculation is  
zero-dimensional, no temperature gradients are resolved within the  
reactor, and the reactor interior and the surface are kept at the same  
temperature.

&gt; 3) You wrote:
&gt;
&gt; setArea(w, 1.0e-4);
&gt; setHeatTransferCoeff(w,0.1);
&gt;
&gt; I am just wondering how the parameters, like 1.0e-4 and 0.1 comes
&gt; from? Cause in our system, we might have significant different
&gt; values of the catalyst surface area as well as the heat transfer
&gt; coefficient.
&gt;
&gt; Thank you very much for your time.
&gt;
Yes, they might be very different. There were only for the example.

